RUUL has 763 outliers (out of 150.000).
It seems a good idea to replace them with another value.

First I’ll try replacing with max from boxplot (which is mean+1.5*(uq-lq)):

outlierReplace = function(dataframe, cols, rows, newValue = NA) {
  if (any(rows)) {
    set(dataframe, rows, cols, newValue)
  }
}
outlierReplace(cs.training, "RUUL", which(cs.training$RUUL>RUULstats[5]), RUULstats[5])
qplot(data = cs.training,
      x = RUUL,
      geom="histogram",
      binwidth = (RUULstats[5]-RUULstats[1])/30,  
      main = "Revolving Utilization of Unsecured Lines", 
      xlab = "RUUL",  
      fill=I("blue"), 
      col=I("red"), 
      alpha=I(0.2),
      xlim=c(RUULstats[1], RUULstats[5]*1.05))

This histogram is pretty different from the one earlier. High peak at 1.

cor(cs.training$RUUL, cs.training$SD, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")   # 0.283004
## [1] 0.283004

This looks a lot better than before. See part5 for more on correlation.

3.1 Imputate Income and Number of Dependents with mean

There are several ways to impute NA values, which we didn’t get into much. I am going to replace NA’s in Income and Dep with the (new) mean values (converted to integers to keep the same datatype), see summary above, because those values seem to be missing at random.

cs.training$Income[is.na(cs.training$Income)] <- as.integer(mean(cs.training$Income, na.rm=TRUE))
cs.training$Dep[is.na(cs.training$Dep)] <- as.integer(mean(cs.training$Dep, na.rm=TRUE))

3.2 Imputate DeptRatio with knn

The NA values in DeptRatio were introced by removing outliers. I will replace these values by looking at similar cases, i.e. imputing with knn. I will remove the id column before imputation, as well as the SD values, since these are the values we want to predict.

# cs.training.temp <- as.data.frame(cs.training[, -c("id", "SD")])
# preProcValues <- preProcess(cs.training.temp, method = c("knnImpute"))
# trainImputed <- predict(preProcValues, cs.training.temp)

This takes a very long time because the dataset is large! I will impute with mean to continue.

cs.training$DebtRatio[is.na(cs.training$DebtRatio)] <- mean(cs.training$DebtRatio, na.rm=TRUE)

4. Generar nuevas variables o features que os parezcan interesantes para el problema.

##4.1 Total number of late days A new feature could be the total number of late days.
For example client1, who was 2 times between 30 and 60 days late (I will take the minimum), will have a total number of at least 30+30=60.
Cient3, who was 1 time between 30 and 60 days late and 1 time 90 or more, will have a total number of at least 30+90=120.

cs.training$LateDays <- cs.training[,no3059] * 30 +
                      cs.training[,no6089] * 60 +
                      cs.training[,no90] * 90

##4.2 log(Income) The differences in income probably will not be linearly correlated with SD, so maybe the logarithm will be a better estimate.
An income of 0 will be a problem here. How many such cases are there?

sum(cs.training$Income==0)   # 1634
## [1] 1634

I will replace those be the mean value, just like NA’s above.

cs.training$Income[cs.training$Income==0] = as.integer(mean(cs.training$Income))
cs.training$logIncome <- log(cs.training[,Income])

##4.3 Debt From DeptRatio and Income we could compute the Debt:

cs.training$Debt <- cs.training[,DebtRatio] * cs.training[,Income]

##4.4 Difference between Income and Dept Maybe a good indicator would be what people have left when they subtract their debt from their income (note: the result can be negative as well). I will call this Slack

cs.training$Slack <- cs.training[,Income] - cs.training[,Debt]
